# wath-core redeploy (agent-owned)

When you change anything that affects the running **wath-core** container, **redeploy immediately yourself** — do not tell the user to redeploy or ask them to confirm.

## Redeploy triggers

Rebuild and recreate **wath-core only** after edits to:

- `packages/engine/**`
- `packages/mcp-server/**`
- `Dockerfile`
- `deploy/podman-compose.yml`
- `deploy/.env` (when `CURSOR_API_KEY`, `WATH_TOKEN`, or other runtime env vars change)

Also redeploy after `npm run build --workspace=@wath/engine --workspace=@wath/mcp-server` when those builds were required for the change to take effect in the container.

## Command (run from repo root)

```bash
npm run build --workspace=@wath/engine --workspace=@wath/mcp-server
podman compose -f deploy/podman-compose.yml up -d --build --force-recreate wath-core
```

## Safety (Podman on inkantation)

- Compose project name: **wath** — container: **wath-core**
- Use **`--force-recreate wath-core` only** — never recreate other stacks (demo-app, inkantation, etc.)
- Never bounce the Podman VM

## Verify after redeploy

```bash
curl -sf http://127.0.0.1:8080/healthz
podman exec wath-core sh -c 'test -n "$CURSOR_API_KEY" && echo ok'
```

Report redeploy success briefly; do not end the turn with "you should redeploy" unless the command failed and you need the user to fix credentials or Podman access.
